<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-939-134  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 939 134.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Dec 4 1989 v23 n49 p121(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's a job offer worth? It pays to tally up bonuses - and costs- from benefits and perquisites.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruhl, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The salary figure of an information systems professional job offerdoes not always reflect an accurate picture of actual income.andP;  Twojob offers at basically the same salary can mean a difference ofas much as $6000, depending on the company's benefits plan.andP;  Aserious erosion in the quality of benefits offered by largeemployers has taken place lately.andP;  Many companies require that theemployee make a significant contribution for family healthinsurance.andP;  Charges for parking can also be hefty.andP;  Many firms nowoffer cafeteria benefit plans where employees receive a givennumber of credits with which they can buy a selection of benefitsfrom a list.andP;  On the positive side, profit-sharing plans canprovide an extra week's pay or more.andP;  Discounts on goods orservices provided by an organization are also beneficial.andP;  Otherfirms subsidize the employee cafeteria or provide free coffee,soda or other extras.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     WagesSalaryEmployee BenefitsComputer industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>